{"title_page": "Sabine Field", "text_new": "{{Infobox venue  |\n  stadium_name  = Sabine Field |\n  image      = Sabine field.jpg\n| caption = Sabine Field, Norwich University\n|  fullname   = Sabine Athletic Field |\n  nickname   = |\n  location   = [[Northfield, Vermont|Northfield]], [[Vermont]] |\n  built      = |\n  opened     = 1921 |\n  Renovated  = 2013 |\n  owner      = [[Norwich University]] |\n  seating_capacity   = 3,000  |\n  tenants     = [[Norwich University|Norwich]] Cadets |\n  dimensions  = |\n}}\n\n'''Sabine Field''' is a 3,000 capacity [[stadium]] in [[Northfield, Vermont|Northfield]], [[Vermont]] on the campus of the NCAA Division III-affiliated [[Norwich University]]. Opened in 1921, it serves as home to the school's [[College football|football]] and track teams.<ref name=\"mediaguide\">{{Citation\n| title = 2007 Norwich University Football Media Guide\n| publisher = Norwich University Sports Information Office\n| url = http://www.norwichathletics.com/sports/fball/2007-08/07_NU_Football_MG_FULL_WEB_DOC.pdf\n| accessdate = 2008-02-22\n}}</ref> The field is named for the son of Dr. George K. Sabine, a member of Norwich's Class of 1868, who provided funds to purchase the athletic field's land<ref name=\"sabine\">{{Citation\n| title = Norwich University Clickable Map: Sabine Field\n| url = http://www.norwich.edu/about/map/ncinfo1b.html#sabine\n| publisher = Norwich University\n| accessdate = 2008-02-22\n|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080216120028/http://www.norwich.edu/about/map/ncinfo1b.html#sabine <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-02-16}}</ref>\n\nSince 1958, Sabine Field area has also been home to a [[World War II|WWII]]-era [[M4 Sherman]] tank named \"Sabine Sally\". Placed in honor of \"the Norwich Men who served in the Armored Forces in World War II\" and dedicated by Norwich alumnus and [[Medal of Honor]] recipient [[James M. Burt|Captain James M. Burt]].<ref>{{Citation\n  | title = In Memorium: CPT James M. Burt, USA, (Ret.)\n  | journal = Norwich Record\n  | publisher = Norwich University Office of Communications\n  | volume = 99\n  | id = 2\n  | issue = Spring 2006\n  | pages = 22\n}}</ref><ref>{{Citation\n  | title = From the University Archives: 45 Years Ago: The Tank Ceremony\n  | journal = Norwich Record\n  | publisher = Norwich University Office of Communications\n  | volume = 96\n  | id = 3\n  | issue = Summer 2003\n  | pages = 3\n}}</ref>\n\n==Alumni March On==\n\nEach fall on the university's Alumni Weekend, Sabine Field hosts the Alumni March On.  At this ceremony, all returning alumni parade by class on to the field with the current year's Corp of Cadets.<ref>{{Citation\n  | title = Homecoming 2005: Full Weekend Coverage\n  | journal = Norwich Record\n  | publisher = Norwich University Office of Communications\n  | volume = 98\n  | id = 4\n  | issue = Fall 2005\n  | pages = 13\u201315\n}}</ref>\n\n==Vermont ghost stories==\n\nThe gate to Sabine Field is a part of Vermont [[ghost story]] lore.  In the tale, the gate to field is said to be guarded by an unseen cadet whose haunting footsteps can be heard.<ref>{{Citation\n  | title = Vermont Ghost Stories and Hauntings\n  | publisher = Vermonter.com\n  | url = http://www.vermonter.com/haunted.asp\n  | accessdate = 2008-02-22\n  | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080202173424/http://www.vermonter.com/haunted.asp\n  | archivedate = 2008-02-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Vermont college football venues}}\n\n{{coord|44|8|29|N|72|39|36|W|display=t|type:landmark}}\n\n[[Category:College football venues]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Vermont]]\n[[Category:American football venues in Vermont]]\n[[Category:Norwich Cadets football]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1921]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in Vermont]]\n\n\n{{Vermont-sports-venue-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox stadium  |\n  stadium_name  = Sabine Field |\n  image      = Sabine field.jpg\n| caption = Sabine Field, Norwich University\n|  fullname   = Sabine Athletic Field |\n  nickname   = |\n  location   = [[Northfield, Vermont|Northfield]], [[Vermont]] |\n  built      = |\n  opened     = 1921 |\n  Renovated  = 2013 |\n  owner      = [[Norwich University]] |\n  seating_capacity   = 3,000  |\n  tenants     = [[Norwich University|Norwich]] Cadets |\n  dimensions  = |\n}}\n\n'''Sabine Field''' is a 3,000 capacity [[stadium]] in [[Northfield, Vermont|Northfield]], [[Vermont]] on the campus of the NCAA Division III-affiliated [[Norwich University]]. Opened in 1921, it serves as home to the school's [[College football|football]] and track teams.<ref name=\"mediaguide\">{{Citation\n| title = 2007 Norwich University Football Media Guide\n| publisher = Norwich University Sports Information Office\n| url = http://www.norwichathletics.com/sports/fball/2007-08/07_NU_Football_MG_FULL_WEB_DOC.pdf\n| accessdate = 2008-02-22\n}}</ref> The field is named for the son of Dr. George K. Sabine, a member of Norwich's Class of 1868, who provided funds to purchase the athletic field's land<ref name=\"sabine\">{{Citation\n| title = Norwich University Clickable Map: Sabine Field\n| url = http://www.norwich.edu/about/map/ncinfo1b.html#sabine\n| publisher = Norwich University\n| accessdate = 2008-02-22\n|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080216120028/http://www.norwich.edu/about/map/ncinfo1b.html#sabine <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-02-16}}</ref>\n\nSince 1958, Sabine Field area has also been home to a [[World War II|WWII]]-era [[M4 Sherman]] tank named \"Sabine Sally\". Placed in honor of \"the Norwich Men who served in the Armored Forces in World War II\" and dedicated by Norwich alumnus and [[Medal of Honor]] recipient [[James M. Burt|Captain James M. Burt]].<ref>{{Citation\n  | title = In Memorium: CPT James M. Burt, USA, (Ret.)\n  | journal = Norwich Record\n  | publisher = Norwich University Office of Communications\n  | volume = 99\n  | id = 2\n  | issue = Spring 2006\n  | pages = 22\n}}</ref><ref>{{Citation\n  | title = From the University Archives: 45 Years Ago: The Tank Ceremony\n  | journal = Norwich Record\n  | publisher = Norwich University Office of Communications\n  | volume = 96\n  | id = 3\n  | issue = Summer 2003\n  | pages = 3\n}}</ref>\n\n==Alumni March On==\n\nEach fall on the university's Alumni Weekend, Sabine Field hosts the Alumni March On.  At this ceremony, all returning alumni parade by class on to the field with the current year's Corp of Cadets.<ref>{{Citation\n  | title = Homecoming 2005: Full Weekend Coverage\n  | journal = Norwich Record\n  | publisher = Norwich University Office of Communications\n  | volume = 98\n  | id = 4\n  | issue = Fall 2005\n  | pages = 13\u201315\n}}</ref>\n\n==Vermont ghost stories==\n\nThe gate to Sabine Field is a part of Vermont [[ghost story]] lore.  In the tale, the gate to field is said to be guarded by an unseen cadet whose haunting footsteps can be heard.<ref>{{Citation\n  | title = Vermont Ghost Stories and Hauntings\n  | publisher = Vermonter.com\n  | url = http://www.vermonter.com/haunted.asp\n  | accessdate = 2008-02-22\n  | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080202173424/http://www.vermonter.com/haunted.asp\n  | archivedate = 2008-02-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Vermont college football venues}}\n\n{{coord|44|8|29|N|72|39|36|W|display=t|type:landmark}}\n\n[[Category:College football venues]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Vermont]]\n[[Category:American football venues in Vermont]]\n[[Category:Norwich Cadets football]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1921]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in Vermont]]\n\n\n{{Vermont-sports-venue-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sabine_Field"}
{"title_page": "Roberts Center", "text_new": "'''Roberts Center''' was a 4,400-seat multi-purpose [[arena]] in [[Chestnut Hill, Massachusetts]].  It opened in 1958.  It was home to the [[Boston College Eagles men's basketball]] and [[Boston College Eagles women's basketball|women's basketball]] teams until the [[Conte Forum]] opened in 1988.<ref>http://newspapers.bc.edu/cgi-bin/bostonsh?a=d&d=bcheights19880201.2.45</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Coord missing|Massachusetts}}\n\n{{Boston College Eagles men's basketball navbox}}\n\n[[Boston College Eagles men's basketball]]\n\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1958]]\n[[Category:Boston College Eagles basketball venues]]\n[[Category:Defunct sports venues in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Defunct indoor arenas in the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct college basketball venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Suffolk County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Indoor arenas in Massachusetts]]\n\n\n{{Massachusetts-stadium-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Roberts Center''' was a 4,400-seat multi-purpose [[arena]] in [[Chestnut Hill, Massachusetts]].  It opened in 1958.  It was home to the [[Boston College Eagles men's basketball]] and [[Boston College Eagles women's basketball|women's basketball]] teams until the [[Conte Forum]] opened in 1988.<ref>http://newspapers.bc.edu/cgi-bin/bostonsh?a=d&d=bcheights19880201.2.45</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Coord missing|Massachusetts}}\n\n{{Boston College Eagles men's basketball navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1958]]\n[[Category:Boston College Eagles basketball venues]]\n[[Category:Defunct sports venues in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Defunct indoor arenas in the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct college basketball venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Suffolk County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Indoor arenas in Massachusetts]]\n\n\n{{Massachusetts-stadium-stub}}[[Boston College Eagles men'